{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"799ae83d-ea84-4578-92b3-bd1ecb588c5c","content":"Since this is a TUnit project, you can use:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nThis filters by the class name portion of the fully qualified name, matching both `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.\n\n> **Note:** TUnit also supports running via `dotnet run` with its native `--treenode-filter` syntax (e.g., `dotnet run -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/**\"`), since the project has `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3f28e29f-22ff-4327-9a5e-111b2267b66b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses its own test adapter and filtering. For TUnit, the class filter uses `--treenode-filter` rather than the standard `--filter` used by MSTest/xUnit/NUnit.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. TUnit works with `dotnet test` and supports the standard `--filter` option as well. The standard dotnet test filter for filtering by class is `FullyQualifiedName~SmsNotificationTests` or `ClassName=SmsNotificationTests`.\n\nBut TUnit also has its own `--treenode-filter` option. Let me think about which is the correct approach.\n\n\nFor TUnit, the recommended approach is using `--treenode-filter` with a pattern like filtering to the specific test class. Though TUnit projects typically run with `dotnet run` since they use `<OutputType>Exe</OutputType>`, `dotnet test` should work if the test adapter is included. With TUnit 0.6.x and the `TUnit` package, standard VSTest filter expressions are supported when using `dotnet test`.\n\nSince you're asking about `dotnet test` specifically, I can use the VSTest filter syntax to target just the `SmsNotificationTests` class by matching against the fully qualified name.","outputTokens":582,"requestId":"480F:2A85DF:7FD750:93D2CD:69FBEA40"},"id":"dce93963-f7ed-4b5e-bab8-fa7b03c31991","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:26:38.0